'''Kushirokahime Shrine''' (くししろかひめじんじゃ) is a shrine in {{ill|lt=Masuda|Q753731|qid=Q753731|1=Masuda, Shimane}}, {{ill|lt=Shimane Prefecture|Q132751|qid=Q132751|1=Shimane Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural shrine|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}}. It is known for three distinctive rites: lion dance, sumo, and needle memorial service.

=== Enshrined deity ===
It enshrines Kushirokahime-no-Mikoto (くしろかひめのみこと) and has merged enshrinement of {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}. In Kushiro-chō, Hamada City, 40 km east, there is the Shikinaisha Kushiro Amenokoketsuhiko-no-Mikoto Shrine.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it was anciently enshrined at Ōhama Ōtanoura. It was later moved to Otsugi-hama in Daidō 1 (806), then sank beneath the sea in Manju 3 (1206) due to high waves, and was moved to Myōjōzan at the current site. After merging Emperor Ōjin, it came to be called “Hama Hachimangū” / “Hama no Hachiman.”

In Meiji 5 (1872) it was ranked as village shrine, in Taishō 8 (1919) as gōsha, and in Shōwa 12 (1937) as prefectural shrine.

=== Legend ===
Shrine tradition says that in ancient times the Kushiro clan sailed from the {{ill|lt=Seto Inland Sea|Q231312|qid=Q231312|1=Seto Inland Sea}} across the {{ill|lt=Sea of Japan|Q27092|qid=Q27092|1=Sea of Japan}} and landed at Kamate Ōhama.

On Mejima (Himejima) and Oshima (Hikoshima) of Kamate Ōtani, Kushirokahime-no-Mikoto and Kushiro Amenokoketsuhiko-no-Mikoto would meet in secret. Kushiro Amenokoketsuhiko-no-Mikoto traveled there with his face covered, but the covering would shift over time; that is said to be the waxing and waning of the moon, in an innocent local legend.

The Kushiro {{ill|lt=Miyatsuko|Q55526942|qid=Q55526942|1=Miyatsuko}} (くししろのみやつこ) were of the same stock as the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Wani clan|1=UNKNOWN}}, and are said to be descendants of Hikotakeushi-no-Mikoto.

